    "key": "570b47b0-90bf-4f65-90d3-475a50f1ea13",
    "name": "Overview",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "Overview",
    "content": "<p>I have degrees from Moray House Edinburgh, Glasgow University, the Open University and Queen Margaret University, and have been a lecturer in film, media and cultural studies at QMU since 2000. Before this, I was a lecturer and tutor at Liverpool John Moores University and Glasgow University. I am secretary of the Scottish Media and Communication Association, and I’m a member of the Melodrama Research Consortium. I am on the editorial board of <em>Film Criticism</em>. I have peer reviewed for various film, media and culture journals, and am currently a peer reviewer for <em>European Journal of Cultural Studies; Images: The International Journal of European Film, Performing Arts and Audiovisual Communication; </em>and <em>Cogent Arts and Humanities.</em> I am a Panel B member of the Scottish Graduate School for Arts and Humanities’ Cohort Development Fund.</p>\n<p><strong>Affiliations/Memberships to Other Organisations:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li>Secretary of the Scottish Media and Communication Association. Member of the Melodrama Research Consortium.</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>Research/Knowledge Exchange Centre Membership:</strong></p>\n<ul>\n<li><a data-id=\"3619\" href=\"/{localLink:3619}\" title=\"Centre for Communication, Cultural and Media Studies\">Centre for Communication, Culture and Media Studies</a> - Full</li>\n</ul>"
  },
  {
    "key": "e7e34d2c-771e-4948-b4d6-6856267ec4e1",
    "name": "Research Interests",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "Research Interests",
    "content": "<p>My primary research interest is film melodrama, and, alongside and related to this, genre and adaptation. My main focus is on film family melodramas – feature films about families, family relations and identities; films which include more pathos than action. <span>I have published work on this subject in various journals, for example <em>Cinema Journal</em>, <em>Journal of British Cinema</em> and <em>Television and Critical Studies in Television</em>. </span></p>\n<p>I also recently edited an international collection of essays on contemporary film and television melodrama – <em>Melodrama in Contemporary Film and Television</em> (Palgrave Macmillan, 2014). I welcome applications from PhD candidates with interests in film melodrama, film genre, film adaptation, European film, and globalised art film.</p>"
  },
  {
    "key": "4e3409dc-d65f-48c6-bd00-865a31d35087",
    "name": "Research Publications",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
    "title": "Research Publications",
    "content": "<p><a href=\"https://eresearch.qmu.ac.uk/browse?type=author&amp;value=Stewart%2C+Michael\" title=\"Dr Michael Stewart - eResearch Repository QMU\" data-anchor=\"?type=author&amp;value=Stewart%2C+Michael\"><span class=\"blue-btn\">Dr Michael Stewart research publications and outputs (QMU eResearch profile)</span></a></p>\n<p> <strong>Currently working on: </strong>An edited collection (with my colleague Robert Munro) to be published by Edinburgh University Press in 2020. This collection comes out of the symposium Robert and I organized at QMU in June 2017, details below.</p>\n<p>Also: <em>Julieta</em> (Almodóvar, 2016) as intercultural text.</p>\n<p>And: Genre and politics in <em>Toni Erdmann</em> (Ade, 2016).</p>\n<p>And: <em>Whisky Galore</em> (2016) as a remake</p>\n<p><strong>Recently organized events: </strong>One day symposium at QMU (with Robert Munro): ‘Adaptation and nation: screen cultures in national, post-national and transnational contexts’, 22<sup>nd</sup> June 2017, details here: <a href=\"https://adaptationandnation.wordpress.com/\">adaptationandnation.wordpress.com/</a></p>\n<p>Two day conference at QMU (with Douglas McNaughton): ‘Becoming Scotland: screen cultures in a small nation’, 28-29 August 2014.</p>\n<p><strong> </strong></p>\n<p><strong>Recently presented papers</strong></p>\n<p>Stewart, M. (2019) ‘Looking for the greatest love of all: social melodrama and the absurd in <em>Toni Erdmann</em>’, at the Media Mixing International Symposium, Lund University, 14<sup>th</sup> March 2019.</p>\n<p>Stewart, M. (2017) ‘Motherhood, memory and punishment: <em>Julieta</em> as transnational guilt’, at the one day symposium, ‘Adaptation and nation: screen cultures in national, post-national and transnational contexts’, Queen Margaret University, Edinburgh, 22<sup>nd</sup> June 2017.</p>\n<p>Stewart, M (2016) ‘Pathos and aftershock: rethinking the national in <em>Calvary</em>’, European screens conference, University of York, 5-7 September 2016.</p>\n<p>Stewart, M. (2015) ‘Melodrama and fatherhood in <em>Shetland</em>’, at the Re-visiting melodrama in contemporary television symposium, University of York, 27<sup>th</sup> March 2015.</p>\n<p>Stewart, M. (2014) ‘Curation, precarity and melodrama in <em>Father of My Children</em>’, Edinburgh film seminar, School of literatures, languages and cultures, University of Edinburgh, 27<sup>th</sup> November 2014.</p>\n<p>Stewart, M. (2014) ‘The death of the father and cultural renewal in <em>The Edge of Heaven</em> and <em>Father of My Children</em>’, Film and media conference, University of London: ‘Visions of identity: global film and media’, 26-28 June 2014.</p>\n<p>Stewart, M. (2013) ‘Melodrama as an enduring form in film and culture’, Keynote address at the 5<sup>th</sup> workshop of the Genre Studies Network: ‘Genre and canons of representation’. Barber Institute of Fine Arts, University of Birmingham, 29<sup>th</sup> April 2013.</p>"
  },
  {
    "key": "7da0df62-5c54-4d65-b7ac-aa14a20b7d43",
    "name": "Funded Projects",
    "ncContentTypeAlias": "centralBlocks",
